thread.title: Jose Bautista HR caps wild 7th inning for Jays, Rangers
thread.title_full: Jose Bautista HR caps wild 7th inning for Jays, Rangers

title: Jose Bautista HR caps wild 7th inning for Jays, Rangers
text:
Blue Jays manager John Gibbons argues with the umpires after Rangers' Rougned Odor is ruled to have scored a run in the 7th inning. (Photo: Nick Turchiaro, USA TODAY Sports)
10 CONNECT 22 TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE TORONTO — Blue Jays right fielder Jose Bautista spared no mercy on a 1-1 fastball that Texas Rangers reliever Sam Dyson had hoped would travel some 55 feet from his outstretched hand to the catcher’s mitt.
Instead, Bautista sent it speeding away on a 431-foot detour to Rogers Centre’s second deck for a three-run homer that capitalized on a massive Rangers defensive failing and negated one of the quirkiest go-ahead tallies in baseball history — one that inspired a Blue Jays protest following a series of umpire conferences and a replay review related to obscure Rule 6.03(a)(3) and that incited fans to throw debris onto the field and chant vulgarities.
Before the frame was complete, the benches would clear, decibel meters would soar and an intensely ebullient crowd began singing Bautista’s first name to the tune of the old soccer song, “Olé Olé Olé.”
It all started in the top of the seventh inning when a harmless throw from behind the plate back out to the mound plated the go-ahead run in a sudden-death playoff game.
After a high ball two to Texas Rangers right fielder Shin-Soo Choo in the top of the seventh inning with a 2-2 score in a deciding American League Division Series Game 5, Toronto Blue Jays catcher Russell Martin casually threw the ball back to reliever Aaron Sanchez on the mound.
Choo happened to be holding his left arm with bat in hand out over the plate as he adjusted his elbow pad when Martin’s throw deflected off Choo’s bat and rolled toward third base. Texas’ Rougned Odor, who had been on third, alertly scampered home as home-plate umpire Dale Scott waved time.
Rangers manager Jeff Banister conferred with Scott, who summoned in the rest of his crew, and then awarded DeShields the plate to make the score 3-2. Martin was given an error.
The crowd erupted, many chanting a two-syllable obscenity and hurling half-filled bottles onto the field, one nearly striking a police officer and another even Martin. Other rubbish chucked from recessed upper section hit fans sitting lower.
The Blue Jays all gathered in the middle of the field away from the debris as security personnel lined the field. Jays manager John Gibbons argued the call, at which point the umpiring crew initiated a replay review to New York.
The game was delayed for about 10 minutes as umpires sorted through the call, and the rubbish — from fans throwing objects onto the field — was cleared.
The Blue Jays began playing the game under a protest rendered moot in the bottom half of the inning when the first three batters reached on three straight Rangers errors — two bobbles from shortstop Elvis Andrus and an errant throw by first baseman Mitch Moreland. After one out was recorded, Josh Donaldson flared the ball a little beyond where Odor was stationed at second base. That ball dropped in to score the tying run.
Bautista then batted next and delivered his game-changing blow. While a few more objects were thrown onto the field — this time in celebration — words were exchanged between the two clubs, leading to a punchless emptying of the benches.
